The '''National Osteoporosis Society''', established in 1986, is the only UK-wide [[Charitable organization|charity]] dedicated to improving the diagnosis, prevention and treatment of [[osteoporosis]]. It is based in [[Camerton, Somerset]], [[England]].<ref>[http://www.nos.org.uk/Page.aspx?pid=223&srcid=262 "About Us"], National Osteoporosis Society.</ref> The income of the charity was about £3.5 million in 2010.<ref name="Charity Commission">{{cite web|url=http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1102712&SubsidiaryNumber=0|title=Charity overview - National Osteoporosis Society|date=31 December 2010|accessdate=2011-11-13|publisher=Charity Commission}}</ref> Three million Britons are affected by osteoporosis.<ref name="Telegraph1">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/7168666/Beer-boosts-bones-and-fends-off-osteoporosis.html|title=Beer boosts bones and fends off osteoporosis|date=08 February 2010|accessdate=2011-11-13|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref>

HRH [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] is the president of the charity,<ref name="Telegraph2">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1386397/Camilla-launches-guide-to-preventing-osteoporosis.html|title=Camilla launches guide to preventing osteoporosis|date=01 Mar 2002|accessdate=2011-11-13|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> which in June 2011 celebrated its 25th anniversary.<ref name="Prince of Wales">{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/the_duchess_of_cornwall_celebrates_25_years_of_the_national__911960818.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110614035452/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/the_duchess_of_cornwall_celebrates_25_years_of_the_national__911960818.html|archivedate=14 June 2011|title=The Duchess of Cornwall celebrates 25 years of the National Osteoporosis Society|publisher=www.princeofwales.gov.uk|date=8 June 2011}}</ref> A public kiss, at a charity reception, between [[Charles, Prince of Wales]] and Camilla, was seen as a step on the road to public acceptance of their relationship.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1409463.stm "Public kiss for Charles and Camilla."] [[BBC News]]. 26 June 2001.</ref> The [[Patronage|patrons]] include actress [[Susan Hampshire]]<ref name="Mail Online">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-557437/My-bones-holes-looked-like-Aero-says-actress-Susan-Hampshire.html|title=My bones had so many holes they looked like an Aero, says actress Susan Hampshire|date=06 April 2008|accessdate=2011-11-13|publisher=Mail Online}}</ref> and journalist [[Maggie Philbin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iofbonehealth.org/iof-women-leaders-roundtable-2008|title=IOF Women Leaders Roundtable 2008|publisher=[[International Osteoporosis Foundation]]|accessdate=26 October 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7918728.stm "Top of the Pops records sold off."] BBC News. 3 March 2009.</ref>

==Research and awards==
The charity, in 1999, reported an increase in incidence of osteoporosis among young women, particularly those who are underweight or who have suffered [[Anorexia nervosa|anorexia]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/health/medical_notes/428878.stm "Medical notes - Osteoporosis."] BBC News. 24 August 1999.</ref> However, in 2000, research by the charity showed that moderate consumption of alcohol can help to reduce bone loss at the hip.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/713698.stm "Moderate drinking 'protects bones'."] BBC News. 15 April 2000.</ref> In 2008 the charity, in conjunction with the [[Order of Mark Master Masons]], awarded around £2.6 million to 14 [[NHS trust]]s to improve osteoporosis services and access to [[Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry|DXA scanners]].<ref name="OSSDP">{{cite web|url=http://www.nos.org.uk/page.aspx?pid=376|title=Osteoporosis Scanning Services Development Project (OSSDP): Improving DXA Services in England and Wales|accessdate=2011-02-11|date=2008|publisher=National Osteoporosis Society}}</ref>

